%T A394368 13,18,11,15,19,13,13,15,14,14,11,16,10,17,12,10,22,15,19,20,11,17,21,
%U A394368 17,13,17,17,20,11,11,16,23,26,17,29,13,15,15,14,11,19,11
%N A394368 Shortest sides z of integer-sided triangles (x <= y <= z) having at least one integral median and such that every integral median m satisfies gcd(x, y, z, m) = 1, ordered by increasing z, then y, then x.
%C A394368 The longest and middle sides are in A394366 and A394367, respectively. The corresponding median values m are in A394369.
%H A394368 Felix Huber, <a href="/A394368/b394368.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10098</a>
%e A394368 5 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (5, 5, 6) the median to z = 6 has length m = 4. It splits z into 3 and 3, yielding two congruent triangles (3, 4, 5), and gcd(5, 5, 6, 4) = 1.
%e A394368 7 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (7, 8, 9) the median to y = 8 has length m = 7. It splits y into 4 and 4, yielding triangles (4, 7, 7) and (4, 7, 9), and gcd(7, 8, 9, 7) = 1.
%e A394368 8 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (8, 14, 14) the medians to y = 14 and z = 14 both have length m = 9. Each splits the side into 7 and 7, yielding triangles (7, 8, 9) and (7, 9, 14), and gcd(8, 14, 14, 9) = 1.
%p A394368 # See Huber link in A394366.
